 or blob-level content diffs. A commit does\nnot directly store \"changed files\", so implementation still needs a tree\ncomparison between the commit tree and its first parent tree, but it should use a\ncheap tree-delta path walk and avoid UI diff APIs or unified diff generation.\nFor root commits, compare against an empty tree. For merge commits, use the\nfirst-parent comparison for v1.\n\nFor renames or rewrites, th\n[TRUNCATED]\ntarget\", not \"this session generated this\ntarget.\"\n\nGitButler's multiple-branches-in-one-worktree model is the main argument for\nturn-scoped precision. A single agent session can mostly build one feature\nbranch while a specific turn produces a bugfix that the user sends to another\nbranch. Whole-session association is therefore useful but not always precise\nenough for review sharing.\n\nRecommended shape:\n\n- store sessions as the durable transcript object\n- start with derived read-time association results from turn evidence\n- let turn evidence highlight or filter the relevant part of the session\n- keep existing explicit target-to-session links as stronger evidence if they\n  already exist\n- allow future relationship metadata to carry optional turn scope if an explicit\n  API/product flow needs durable links\n\nIn other words, turn scope should refine a session relationship. It should not\nmove transcript ownership onto branches, changes, commits, or pull requests.\n\n## Persist Or Recompute\n\nThe turn layer could be stored directly, or some of it could be recomputed from\nexisting records and Git state.\n\nReasons to persist turns:\n\n- preserves exact capture boundaries\n- preserves repository state at the time of capture\n- supports later association even after branches or worktree state changed\n- makes handoff and review timelines cheaper to query\n\nReasons to recompute some association:\n\n- avoids prematurely committing to a wrong relationship\n- keeps durable metadata smaller\n- allows better algorithms later without rewriting old data\n\nMy current take: persist the observation, not the conclusion. Store turn objects\nand environment snapshots. Use them to compute association results at read time.\nPersist relationships only if an explicit API/product flow later needs durable\nlinks.\n\n## Access Patterns\n\nThe model should make these reads efficient.\n\nDefine the read surface around the two product use cases:\n\n- `getSessionTimeline(session_key, window?)`: returns turn summaries plus\n  hydrated records for a bounded handoff window\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:22:50.033Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}